                        <div id="content" class="hfeed">
                            <article class="post-158531 post type-post status-publish hentry category-private-lives tag-football tag-sports-injuries des-football des-sports-injuries news_keywords-football news_keywords-sports-injury" id="post-158531">
                                <header class="postHeader">
                                    <div class="postKicker">
                                        <span class="kicker"><a href="//opinionator.blogs.nytimes.com/category/private-lives/?module=BlogCategory&amp;version=Blog Post&amp;action=Click&amp;contentCollection=Opinion&amp;pgtype=Blogs&amp;region=Header">Private Lives</a></span>
                                    </div>
                                    <h1 itemprop="headline" class="entry-title">Rewatching the Theismann Injury</h1>
                                    <div class="story-meta-footer">
                                        <address class="byline author vcard" itemprop="author creator" itemtype="//schema.org/Person">
				By Chris Bachelder			</address>
                                        <!-- date published --><time class="dateline " datetime="2015-11-18T08:32:29+00:00" itemprop="datePublished">November 18, 2015 3:32 am</time>
                                        <!-- date updated --><span class="visually-hidden updated">November 18, 2015 3:32 am</span><button class="button comments-button  theme-kicker" data-skip-to-para-id="">
</button>
                                    </div>
                                </header>
                                <div class="entry-content">
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"></p>
                                    <div class="inlineModule">
                                        <div class="entry">
                                            <div class="thumb"><img alt="Private Lives" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/blogs_v3/firstperson/firstperson45.png" width="50" height="50"></div>
                                            <p class="summary"> <a href="//opinionator.blogs.nytimes.com/category/private-lives/">Private Lives:</a> Personal essays on the news of the world and the news of our lives.
                                            </p>
                                        </div>
                                    </div><br>
                                    <div class="w480">
                                        <figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/11/18/opinion/18PRIVATE/18PRIVATE-blog480.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span>
                                            <div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/11/18/opinion/18PRIVATE/18PRIVATE-blog480.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/11/18/opinion/18PRIVATE/18PRIVATE-blog480.jpg" id="100000004044519"
                                                    width="480" height="589" alt="">
                                                <meta itemprop="height" content="589">
                                                <meta itemprop="width" content="480">
                                            </div>
                                            <figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text"></span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Niv Bavarsky</span>
                                            </figcaption>
                                        </figure>
                                    </div>
                                    <p></p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">There has perhaps never been a more memorable play in football &#x2014; or even all of American sports &#x2014; than the one that ended the career of the Washington Redskins quarterback Joe Theismann, 30 years ago today.
                                        Since that play, N.F.L. quarterbacks have attempted nearly half a million passes, and we have never again seen (or heard) such skeletal trauma.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">As Theismann was sacked by New York Giants linebacker Lawrence Taylor, the two bones of his lower leg snapped (he later said it sounded like &#x201C;two muzzled gunshots&#x201D;). He suffered a compound or open fracture,
                                        meaning bone broke through skin. There has been plenty of brutality and gore in the subsequent three decades of televised sports, plenty of unwatchable replays, but nothing quite like this. An ESPN poll found that
                                        the Theismann injury was the &#x201C;most shocking moment in football history.&#x201D;</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">But what does it mean to call the play <em>memorable</em>? Suppose you were asked to write down everything you remember about the play in 60 seconds. What would make your list?</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Not long ago, I conducted this exercise in memory. Before watching the replay on YouTube &#x2014; across the room from my computer monitor, peeking through my fingers &#x2014; I remembered that the play happened in
                                        prime time, during a &#x201C;Monday Night Football&#x201D; telecast. At that time, Monday night games began at 9 p.m. on the East Coast. I was 14 in 1985, and I was permitted to stay up to watch the first half.
                                        So I knew the injury must have occurred in the first half (though I did not remember that it was early second quarter, a first-and-10 from near midfield, the scored tied at 7-7).</p>
                                    <div class="w480 youtube-video-container">
                                        <div class="youtube-video" data-youtube-id="mznBvAGScdg" data-start="">
                                            <div class="thumb"><img src="https://img.youtube.com/vi/mznBvAGScdg/0.jpg">
                                                <div class="playButton">
                                                    <div class="arrow"></div>
                                                </div>
                                            </div>
                                        </div>
                                    </div>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span id="more-158531"></span></p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">I remembered that the game took place at R.F.K. Stadium in Washington, and I remembered that the Redskins&#x2019; opponent was the New York Giants. I remembered that the injury occurred when Taylor sacked Theismann.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">As someone who spent countless childhood hours drawing the helmets of all professional football teams, I remembered vividly the single anachronistic bar of Theismann&#x2019;s face mask.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">I remembered that Taylor jumped on Theismann&#x2019;s back, and that the leg was broken as Taylor slid and spun down Theismann&#x2019;s body.<br> I remembered that the injury was not visible from the regular camera
                                        angle.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Like everyone else, I remembered that Taylor, obviously distraught, stood and beckoned frantically to the Redskins medical staff on the sideline. I vividly remembered Taylor looking down at Theismann. I remembered that
                                        he put his hands briefly to his head, that archetypal expression of shock and anguish. Not his head, though &#x2014; his <em>helmet</em> &#x2014; and so it was as if the equipment of his profession interfered with
                                        his basic human response.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">I remembered, most powerfully, the horror of the reverse angle, slow-motion replay. I remembered that it was shown repeatedly, but in fact it was shown only twice.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Finally, I remembered Theismann being wheeled off the field on a stretcher, though in fact he was carried off the field on a wheeled stretcher.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">As it turns out, my memory of the play was fairly extensive and fairly accurate, though with one conspicuous omission. What I failed to remember &#x2014; and what strikes me now as a salient and poignant detail of the
                                        five-second episode &#x2014; is that the injury occurred on a trick play. My adolescent brain, sifting the traumatic event for significant data, did not hold on to a piece of basic information &#x2014; the Redskins
                                        were trying to run a flea-flicker, a little razzle-dazzle.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">But there it is on the replay: Theismann takes the snap under center and hands to the running back John Riggins. Nicknamed &#x201C;The Diesel,&#x201D; Riggins is hardly known for guile or dissimulation, but he takes
                                        three quick steps and then pitches the ball back to Theismann, who intends to throw a deep pass. You can see Theismann gazing briefly downfield before his pocket collapses like a dying star.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The Redskins, that is, are trying to do something unconventional, surprising. For this down at least they are trying to play this vicious and fundamentally conservative sport with a little grace and levity, a little
                                        sandlot flair. (In the Washington playbook, the flea-flicker has the golden name of &#x201C;The Throwback Special.&#x201D;) This trick play, when executed well, has a certain elegant wit. It looks like one thing
                                        but it&#x2019;s really another thing, like a well-turned pun or punch line, and like a joke it runs on precision and incongruity. A playful play, the well-run flea-flicker elicits not just our applause but our mirth,
                                        our laughter.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">While my 14-year-old mind did not find the flea-flicker significant enough to retain, three decades later, at 44, I find that I&#x2019;m moved by the chasm &#x2014; suddenly so obvious and prominent &#x2014; between
                                        heady design and disappointing outcome, between idealistic grandeur and violent calamity. It certainly must have been said before that middle age is that time when we begin to square ambition with reality, to understand
                                        that forces far beyond our control have far more power than we have previously granted. Luck and contingency certainly count for as much as skill, dedication and foresight, and in every scheme there lies the seed
                                        of disappointment, even disaster. In middle age, we begin to see that shortcoming is the rule.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">What roles, what tasks, are executed to glorious conception in my life? The classes I teach have no chance to live up to my grand syllabuses and course design. The novels (or even short essays) I write can never match
                                        my ineffable sense of their potential. When I&#x2019;m with my daughters, I typically do not exhibit the patience or generosity or attentiveness that I frequently promise myself, while they sleep, to bring to the
                                        day.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Yes, in its shocking particulars the Theismann injury was a fluke, a statistical outlier. I know it doesn&#x2019;t prove anything, except perhaps its own radical unlikelihood. But it is not difficult, at 44, to see
                                        this failed flea-flicker as an allegory or parable, a reminder of the dark underside of our aspirations, so elegant, so ambitious.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">I didn&#x2019;t remember it but I see it clearly now. It&#x2019;s right there on the replay: When the Redskins break their beautifully formed huddle &#x2014; inside of which Theismann has called his final play &#x2014;
                                        the players clap in unison and jog eagerly to the line of scrimmage. Even Theismann jogs. It&#x2019;s easy to see they&#x2019;ve got something special planned.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em><a href="//www.artsci.uc.edu/departments/english/profiles/chris_bachelder.html">Chris Bachelder</a> is the author of the forthcoming novel &#x201C;The Throwback Special.&#x201D;</em></p>
                                </div>
                                <footer class="entry-footer">
                                    <button class="button comments-button theme-speech-bubble"></button>
